(Worked Examples) Tj
T*
(Worked Example 1) Tj
T*
(1. Start with an example based on following how a DNA code leads to a protein.) Tj
T*
(2. Identify the exact idea in transcription, translation, and the role of ribosomes that) Tj
T*
(the question is testing.) Tj
T*
(3. Apply the correct method for Protein Synthesis step by step without skipping) Tj
T*
(reasoning.) Tj
T*
(4. Check the final answer and explain why it is correct.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Worked Example 2) Tj
T*
(1. Choose a second example that still focuses on gene expression sequence questions.) Tj
T*
(2. Break the task into smaller parts and link each part to the rule being used.) Tj
T*
(3. Point out how to avoid mixing DNA and RNA roles while solving it.) Tj
T*
(4. Review the result and connect it back to the topic overview.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Common Mistakes) Tj
T*
(- Misunderstanding the core focus of Protein Synthesis: transcription, translation, and) Tj
T*
(the role of ribosomes.) Tj
T*
(- Mixing DNA and RNA roles.) Tj
T*
(- Jumping to an answer without showing the steps or reasoning clearly.) Tj
T*
(- Practising Protein Synthesis without checking whether the method matches the question) Tj
T*
(being asked.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Study Tips) Tj
T*
(- Rewrite the overview of Protein Synthesis in your own words after studying it.) Tj
T*
(- Use short exercises built around gene expression sequence questions before trying) Tj
T*
(harder tasks.) Tj
T*
